That is an EXCELLENT idea. I know their triage and hospital facilities are second only to a full fledged hospital ship and they have the helicopter facilities for rapid medical transport as well as supporting rescue and recon ops. I worked on some improvements needed to the med facilities on those ships right after they were delivered from Ingalls. Not that Ingalls forgot to install them, just that they were late Shipalts with late funding that was not enough to cover Ingalls' Change Order charges. So the Navy yards got a crack at them instead.

They can carry 1200 Marines so that berthing area can be medical wards for patients with less than dire medical needs.

Communications spaces can be turned into a great 911 center to monitor and/or control dispatch of emergency personnel. Being a ship and if buoyed far enough off shore, cutting the moor and putting full power on the twin screws could allow the ship to ride on up and over an incoming tsunami. A major earthquake would only rattle a couple of small items off the shelves.

Only a direct hit from a locomotive sized asteroid could take it out.
</post>
