<post author="SnowLeopard" datetime="2007-01-14T11:12:00" id="p39">
<quote orig_author="Dreadnought">
....... The Belgrano (ex Phoenix) should have never been there. Argentina should have known the Brits would have subs in the area having to come that distance to defend the Faulklands should have told Argentina the Brits would bring other toys to the game thus not go home "empty handed". Obviously they must have figured the Brits would only bring surface combatants. Its still debatable whether it was the right decision or not but what are you going to do when you are at war?........

</quote>

Comme ce, Comme ca. IMHO, two issues. First of all, there is a question of how hard they expected the Brits to fight for the island. "what are you going to do when you are at war?" Maybe they didn't expect the Brit's really to go to war. After all, maybe a lot of people didn't expect how far it would go. When the Sheffield was hit, one of the news magazine headlines was on the lines of "A little war turns nasty" (wtte).

Secondly, a primary belief in war, at least for some, is to make the other guy want to stop fighting. Obviously, if you kill him, that is accomplished. But more than that, it is to shock him to how bad war is, to make him go back to the negotiation table. That shock is known as THUNDERCLAP. Thunderclap might be, for example, nuking his leading city (maybe not the capital because you want the negotiation teams) on the first day of the war.

But sinking a high price item, such as a cruiser for such a country, is a version of THUNDERCLAP. You make the war VERY expensive for him.

Whether sinking the cruiser achieved the purpose of THUNDERCLAP is debateable. But it did accomplish one thing. Having lost the cruiser, they kept the carrier in port so not to chance losing it, too.
-------------------------------------------------------
("Captain, they're PIS*ED!"--Lyta Alexander after Sheraton used hidden nukes to destroy part of the enemy fleet, (w,stte), "B V")
