Unfortunately, this guy's account is pretty much on the money, if a little
over dramatized. There's already a clip on YouTube of the band's
performance of &quot;Ain't Talkin' 'Bout Love&quot; from near the end of the show and
Eddie's guitar is drastically out of tune from banging it around during his
preceding solo spot and he just can't compensate with his diminished playing
skills:

http://youtube.com/watch?v=Ld4n_1Wwl9c

Note that at the very last second of the clip at the end of the song, Eddie
throws his guitar at or to his tech.

I can't say the tour is &quot;unraveling,&quot; as there's really been only two bum
shows so far, this one and the KC show a couple weeks ago. However, there
*are* nagging problems mostly to do with very iffy arena sound and monitor
and guitar tuning issues pretty much revolving around Eddie Take that into
account with the fact Eddie fired his regular guitar tech (who went online
on a guitar gear message board and hinted Eddie was impossible to work for)
only a couple weeks before the tour started makes me wonder if the current
tech is simply unable to cope with Eddie's undoubtedly difficult primadonna
music and personal issues or worse (or perhaps better, heh) is fucking with
Eddie on purpose just because Ed's such a prick to work for these days.

It is rather funny that the supposed weak links of this lineup, being Roth
and Eddie's young son have more than surpassed any expectations while Eddie
just can't seem to consistently keep it together onstage.

I've seen hundreds of bands, many shows in every sort of venue possible and
it simply appears Eddie and by virtue the band is having an unprecedented
amount of sound issues from monitors, to earpiece volume to amps to his
guitar being constantly out of tune compared to anyone else I've ever seen
including Van Halen up through '98 and it actually appears to be getting
worse, not better on a show by show basis. One band whom I've seen have a
lot of guitar issues live, U2, always has The Edge's guitar tech right there
with a new guitar if Edge breaks a string or has a instrument problem. It's
astounding Eddie Van Halen is going night after night with these sort of
problems through big chunks of the show.

Regarding the guitar cable issue many people wonder about, yeah, a lot of
musicians still use cables for a variety of reasons, one being wireless
technology is far from sonically perfect (although in a huge arena, no one
could probably notice the difference, especially concerning Eddie's tone
which is pretty harsh and ratty these days), plus the transmitter/receiver
can pick up interference or outside broadcasts (see the infamous scene in
&quot;Spinal Tap&quot;) especially outdoors. The thing is, a guy like Eddie who moves
all over the stage and is constantly tripping over and fiddling with the
cable, he really should be wireless and in fact, always was up until 1998
and his tone never suffered live - in fact it sounds worse the past couple
tours than it ever has. Being chained to a cable, he doesn't go out on the
ramp at all and is pretty much limited to his 25 feet of space around his
rig.

I'm going to the first show at Staples Arena in LA on 11/20, and have a 5th
row seat right on Eddie's side like the unrepentant VH nerdliner I still am.
It's tough to say which I'm looking forward to more, this lineup playing the
songs from the first 6 albums or a true onstage meltdown of Chernobyl sized
proportions. To be fair, when I saw the mediocre Sammy Hagar reunion in
'04, that tour was getting slammed because Eddie was absolutely wasted on
stage at most shows and they wound up turning in one of the most solid shows
of the tour at the Staples show I caught. Thus it's fair to assume they'll
bring their &quot;A&quot; game to LA for the hometown crowd which I expect will
welcome these guys like conquering heroes.

T.B.
</POST>
