<HEADLINE>
Contestant injured in Finland's Sauna World Championships in
stable condition
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
HELSINKI, Aug. 8 (Xinhua)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Finnish contestant injured in the Sauna World Championships held in Finland
Saturday evening is currently in stable condition and being treated in a
hospital in Finland's capital Helsinki, Finnish police said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Sauna World Championships held in Heinola, southern Finland was
suspended because of a tragic accident on Saturday evening, when a Russian
contestant died and a Finnish contestant seriously injured in men's finals.
</P>
<P>
The last two finalists, Vladimir Ladyzhenskiy from Russia and five-time
championship winner Timo Kaukonen from Finland collapsed in the competition
after staying in a sauna room with a temperature of 110 degrees Celsius for more
than six minutes. The competition was suspended immediately when the staff found
the situation had exceeded the limits of men's health. Both contestants were
taken out of the sauna room and given first aid.
</P>
<P>
However, the Russian man, who is over 60 years old, died on the spot and the
Finnish man, who is about 40, was sent to a hospital in Lahti in southern
Finland for more medical treatment on severe scald. He has been transferred to a
hospital in Helsinki and the current condition is stable.
</P>
<P>
Finnish police told the media on Sunday after preliminary investigation that the
death of the Russian contestant Ladyzhenskiy has nothing to do with crime. Both
contestants have passed the physical examination and should be responsible for
the accident by themselves. The cause of Ladyzhenskiy's death in being further
investigated.
</P>
<P>
The competition organization emphasized that there was no imperfection of the
security measures during the men's finals. However, they have decided not to
hold the event anymore in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Sauna World Championships has been held in Heinola annually since 1999, and
this year's event drew over 140 contestants from 15 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
