<HEADLINE>
Plane overshoots runway at Teterboro Airport in New Jersey, U.S.
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
NEW YORK, Oct. 1 (Xinhua)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A plane has overshot the runway at Teterboro Airport in New Jersey, the United
States on Friday, according to the NBC report.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said the pilot of the corporate jet went "too long" on the landing
and the plane hit an "arrester bed," which crumbled under the weight of the
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately clear what caused the plane to go into the safety bed --
aerated cement blocks that are designed to fall apart under the weight of a
plane, stopping it from veering out of control at the end of runway.
</P>
<P>
There were no injuries reported.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which operates
the airport, was quoted as saying that seven passengers and two pilots were
aboard the G-4 Gulfstream.
</P>
<P>
The incident occurred at about 1:45 p.m. local time Friday, she said.
</P>
<P>
Teterboro, near New York City, handles primarily smaller private and corporate
jets and is among the busiest in the country for that class of airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC id="XIN_ENG_20101124.0253" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
Cuba continues investigation on jailed U.S. contractor
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
HAVANA, Nov. 24 (Xinhua)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cuban authorities have continued to investigate U.S. contractor Alan Gross,
arrested a year ago on espionage charges, Attorney General Dario Delgado said
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Delgado chaired the 10th International Criminal Sciences Meeting 2010  at the
Havana Convention Palace until Thursday, attended by 300 specialists from over
20 nations from Latin America, Europe, Asia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The investigation is still in the same situation. Our investigation has not
completed yet. We are still working and when we finish, we will give an official
answer," Delgado said.
</P>
<P>
Gross was arrested on Dec. 3, 2009 at the Havana Airport, and was accused of
providing internet satellite communication equipment to the anti-Castro groups
based on the island.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has called for his release on humanitarian grounds, saying that Gross
was only providing an internet connection to the Cuban Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
The detainee's wife, Judy Gross, wrote to Cuban leader Raul Castro in August to
express regret for her husband's work in Cuba. The Cuban authorities have
allowed Gross' wife to visit him at least once at a military hospital in Havana
where he was detained.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Gross has criticized the White House for not doing enough and described her
husband as "a victim caught in the crossfire between the two foes of the old
Cold War."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department recently dismissed an alleged plan to exchange Gross
for one of the five Cubans imprisoned since 1998 in the United States under
espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
The case has been handled by officials of both countries when they met in Havana
and Washington on migration and other bilateral issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC id="XIN_ENG_20101201.0249" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
Cuban Jewish community denies links with jailed U.S. contractor
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
HAVANA, Dec. 1 (Xinhua)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leaders of Jewish groups in Cuba denied on Wednesday they have any contact with
jailed U.S. contractor Alan Gross, who was arrested a year ago over charges of
spying.
</P>
<P>
Adela Dworin, vice president of the "Jewish Patronage," said, "I am very sorry
for what happened to Gross," adding that "the saddest thing is that he wanted to
engage the Jewish community, which is totally strange to his activities."
</P>
<P>
Mayra Levy, official from the Havana Sephardic Hebrew Center, said she had never
met Gross and he never visited the institution.
</P>
<P>
Currently, some 1,500 Jews live in Cuba with most of them in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Gross was arrested on Dec. 3, 2009, at the Havana airport for allegations of
providing Internet satellite communication equipment to the anti-Castro groups
based on the island.
</P>
<P>
Though he has been imprisoned for a year, he has not been officially charged
yet.
</P>
<P>
U.S. calls for his release on humanitarian grounds and ensured that Gross was
only providing Internet connection to the Cuban Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
The detainee's wife, Judy Gross, wrote in August to Cuban President Raul Castro
to express regrets for her husband's work in Cuba. Cuban authorities have
allowed Gross's wife to visit him at least once at a military hospital in Havana
where he was detained.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Gross has criticized the White House for not doing enough and described her
husband as "a victim caught in the crossfire between the two foes of the old
Cold War."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department dismissed recently an alleged plan to exchange Gross
with one of the five Cubans imprisoned since 1998 in the United States under
espionage charges. The case has been handled by officials of both countries when
they met in Havana and Washington on migration and other bilateral issues.
</P>
